  "faq": [
    {
      "question": "What is Amazon Pay?",
      "answer": "Amazon Pay is a digital wallet that lets shoppers pay on participating merchant sites using the payment and shipping details stored in their Amazon account."
    },
    {
      "question": "Do I need a payment service provider (PSP) or acquirer if I add Amazon Pay?",
      "answer": "Often yes—Amazon Pay is a payment method, and many merchants connect it through an existing PSP/ecommerce platform integration. The exact setup depends on your platform and region."
    },
    {
      "question": "Why are some Amazon Pay payments declined?",
      "answer": "Declines can happen for many reasons such as insufficient funds, issuer or account restrictions, risk checks, data mismatches, or configuration issues. Review the decline reason data available in your integration and compare patterns across checkout steps."
    },
    {
      "question": "Where is Amazon Pay available?",
      "answer": "Amazon Pay availability varies by country and program. Confirm supported merchant and shopper countries directly in Amazon Pay’s documentation or merchant onboarding materials for your region."
    },
    {
      "question": "How do refunds and cancellations work with Amazon Pay?",
      "answer": "Refunds are initiated through Amazon Pay merchant tools and/or via your platform/PSP connection, depending on how you integrated. Make sure your customer support and accounting teams know the correct process for your setup."
    },
    {
      "question": "How are disputes handled for Amazon Pay transactions?",
      "answer": "Dispute handling can differ from standard card chargeback flows. Use Amazon Pay’s merchant tools and guidance for responding to disputes and tracking outcomes, and keep order/shipping evidence organized."
    }
  ],
